In a **Rotated Binary Search (RBS)** problem like **Search in Rotated Sorted Array**,
the array was originally sorted but then rotated at some pivot point, creating two separately sorted portions.
The idea is first to **find the pivot**, which is the index of the largest element where the rotation occurs 
(the point where `arr[i] > arr[i+1]`). If no pivot is found, the array was never rotated and a normal binary search can be applied on the entire array.
If a pivot exists, the array effectively becomes two sorted subarrays: one from the start to the pivot and another from the pivot+1 to the end.
Since binary search only works on sorted ranges, we decide which of these two halves could contain the target by comparing the target with 
the first element of the array. Then we run a standard binary search on that half. This keeps the time complexity **O(log n)** 
because both pivot finding and binary search operate logarithmically.


